<speak version="1.0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2001/10/synthesis" xmlns:mstts="https://www.w3.org/2001/mstts" xml:lang="en-IN"><voice name="en-IN-Diya:DragonHDLatestNeural" parameters="temperature=0.55"><break time="700ms"/><mstts:express-as style="calm" styledegree="0.4"><prosody rate="-1%"><p>A homeowner takes a thirty year mortgage and repays it after four years because she moves to another city. She has not defaulted. The lender receives principal early. For the investor, a long stream of expected interest has suddenly become cash that must be reinvested.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Mortgage cash flow models need a common way to describe how quickly borrowers prepay. The Public Securities Association standard prepayment model, usually called <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub>, is a market convention that expresses an assumed prepayment path. It is not a forecast that borrowers have agreed to follow.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Prepayment is unscheduled principal returned before the contractual amortisation schedule requires it. Borrowers refinance, sell property, use savings, or otherwise repay early. Scheduled principal and unscheduled principal must be separated because they respond to different assumptions.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Conditional prepayment rate, or C P R, expresses an annualised proportion of the remaining pool assumed to prepay, conditional on surviving to that period. A six percent C P R does not mean six percent of original balances prepays every year forever. The base declines as loans amortise, prepay, and default.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Single monthly mortality, or S M M, converts the annual assumption into a monthly rate. Conceptually, the monthly rate is one minus the twelfth root of one minus the annual C P R. At a six percent annual C P R, the corresponding monthly rate is a little above one half of one percent.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>One hundred <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> begins with a low C P R for a new mortgage pool. The benchmark increases by zero point two percentage points each month until it reaches six percent in month thirty, then remains at six percent. The ramp reflects the idea that brand new borrowers usually need time before refinancing, moving, or otherwise prepaying.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Fifty <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> applies half the benchmark speed. Two hundred <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> applies twice the benchmark speed. At month thirty and beyond, fifty <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> corresponds to three percent C P R, while two hundred <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> corresponds to twelve percent, subject to the convention&apos;s calculation.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>The number is a comparison language. Saying one pool is modelled at two hundred <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> lets investors compare an assumed speed with the standard curve. It does not establish that the pool&apos;s actual borrowers will behave at that speed.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Seasoning affects where the pool sits on the ramp. A pool with average loan age of twenty months is not treated like brand new production under a seasoning aware application. Loan age, rate incentive, geography, borrower characteristics, housing turnover, and underwriting all influence observed prepayment.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Refinancing incentive is powerful. When market mortgage rates fall below borrowers&apos; existing rates by enough to overcome costs and friction, prepayment can accelerate. When rates rise, refinancing slows and mortgages can remain outstanding longer.</p></prosody></mstts:express-as></voice></speak>
<speak version="1.0" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2001/10/synthesis" xmlns:mstts="https://www.w3.org/2001/mstts" xml:lang="en-IN"><voice name="en-IN-Diya:DragonHDLatestNeural" parameters="temperature=0.55"><mstts:express-as style="calm" styledegree="0.4"><prosody rate="-1%"><p>That creates contraction risk. Principal returns faster than expected, the security&apos;s average life shortens, and premium investors may lose expected interest. Reinvestment happens when comparable yields may be lower.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Slow prepayment creates extension risk. Principal remains outstanding longer, duration increases, and investors stay exposed when they may prefer cash back. A security expected to behave like a short asset can become a long one without a borrower default.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Weighted average life measures the average time each unit of principal remains outstanding. It differs from final legal maturity. <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> assumptions affect projected principal dates and therefore expected life, price sensitivity, and yield.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Premium and discount change investor preference. An investor paying above par generally dislikes unexpected fast principal because premium is recovered sooner with less interest. An investor buying below par may benefit from principal returning at par sooner, though other risks remain.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Burnout describes how a pool can become less responsive after repeated refinancing opportunities. Borrowers able and willing to refinance may already have left. The remaining borrowers can be constrained by credit, loan size, documentation, inertia, or economics. A constant relationship between rate incentive and prepayment may then overstate future speed.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Defaults and prepayments both remove performing balance but have opposite credit meanings. Prepayment returns principal. Default interrupts payment and may recover only part later. A model that combines all balance reduction as principal received invents cash.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Servicing and product terms also matter. Prepayment penalties where lawful, refinancing friction, borrower outreach, assumability, loan size, and documentation can change behaviour. Historical <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> speeds from another market or product are not automatically transferable.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Sifma&apos;s uniform practices provide the authoritative convention for <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub>. Securities disclosures can show prepayment assumptions and sensitivity. Neither source can supply an Indian home loan pool&apos;s future speed without its data and a reasoned behavioural model.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Suppose a mortgage security is valued at one hundred <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub>. Run fifty, one hundred, two hundred, and stress paths. Observe interest, principal, weighted average life, tranche amortisation, extension, and reinvestment. The point is not to crown one curve correct; it is to see what the investment depends upon.</p><break time="260ms"/><p>Indian housing loans in Chennai and Mumbai require their own evidence. Do not invent a <sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> number. Collect loan age, coupon, remaining term, prior prepayment, refinancing rates, property turnover, borrower type, channel, and seasonality before selecting or calibrating a speed.</p><break time="260ms"/><p><sub alias="P S A">PSA</sub> is a ruler for timing, not a prophecy about people. It helps investors measure how a mortgage security changes when borrowers exercise the right to leave early.</p></prosody></mstts:express-as></voice></speak>
